02. Scanning and Enumeration
____________________________
- Nmap, Nessus, Nikto, etc
SCAN both TCP side and UDP side

COMMANDS
########
whatweb -v tesla.com
wireshark &
go to the domain
then analysis the traffic interactions with the domain
We need to confirm that theres a [SYN], [SYN, ACK],[ACK]  means that the port is open
if it shows it means we can confirm that connection

nmap --help
nmap -sU     	(UDP scan)

Ping sweep:
nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24

-T4 - 1 speed (not a stealthy scan)
nmap -T4 192.168.1.254
MAKE SURE TO SCAN EVERY PORT

Staging:
nmap -T4 -p- 192.168.1.254

Which ports are open ?

add them to this scan vv
vv
Now scan these ports using:
Nmap -T4 -A p53,80,111,443,514 192.168.1.254

(Go to scan) Not recommened , worst case scenario
nmap -T4 -A -p- 192.168.1.254
we can develop this futher:


Saves results:
nmap -T4 -p- 192.168.1.254 -oA client
Can write a script that adds all these ports to this scan:
nmap -T4 -A p<saved client files> 192.168.1.54

UDP SCANS ------
nmap -sU -T4 192.168.1.254
cant trust a UDP scan (time consuming , let nexxus find it)



NMAP SCRIPTS -------
ls /usr/share/nmap/scripts/
vulnerability scanning:

nmap -p 443 --script=all 

gives a rating on all the ciphers:
nmap -p 443 --script=ssl-enum-ciphers tesla.com
and then the least strength of a cipher

Vulnerabiliy Scanning:
Download and install nessus:
dpkg -i Nessus.deb
make account
click new scan
click basic scan
type in targets seperated by comma at newscan/basic scan
in the discovery section you can select all ports rather then specify specific ones
scan type: default , unless its web scan 
go to My scan > then select Launch

nikto -h https://tesla.com

msfconsole
search portscan
use auxiliary/portscan/syn
set ports 1-65535
set rhosts 192.168.1.254
run
will tell you if a ports open or closed , pretty much it 

but what are you looking for ?

search tomcat


